---
description: Observability, monitoring, and analytics for VidShield AI
globs: backend/app/core/logging*, backend/app/core/metrics*, infra/monitoring/**, frontend/src/**/analytics*
---

Observability scope (see PRD):
- System logs (structured, with correlation IDs for requests, jobs, and video/stream IDs).
- AI pipeline monitoring (latency, token usage, model, errors for GPT-4o/Whisper).
- Latency monitoring for API, video processing, moderation pipeline, and storage.
- Error tracking (e.g. centralized error reporting such as Sentry).
- Usage analytics (videos processed, moderation throughput, policy violations, alerts fired).

Dashboard and reporting:
- Analytics: throughput, violation rates, policy effectiveness, live stream health, processing latency.
- Real-time: live stream status, moderation queue depth, alert banners.
- Expose metrics in a form consumable by CloudWatch, Prometheus, or Grafana; keep dashboards defined in code or config where possible.

Rules:
- Use structured logging (JSON or key-value) with consistent fields: request_id, video_id, stream_id, job_id, user_id, level, message, duration_ms.
- Do not log PII, passwords, or raw tokens; mask or redact in log pipelines if needed.
- Instrument critical paths: frame extraction, Whisper calls, LLM/vision calls, moderation workflow, S3 operations, webhook delivery.
- Alerts for critical failures (e.g. pipeline down, OpenAI errors above threshold, queue backlog); avoid alert fatigue.

Do not:
- Rely on ad-hoc print statements for production diagnostics.
- Expose internal error details or stack traces to end-users; keep detailed errors in logs only.
- Add observability as an afterthought; include logging and metrics in new features by default.
